<h2 id="SurpCons">5. Surprising Consequences</h2>

<p>
Mally called theorems (1), (2), (7), (22) and (27)&ndash;(35)
&ldquo;surprising&rdquo; (<em>befremdlich</em>) or even
&ldquo;paradoxical&rdquo; (<em>paradox</em>). He viewed (34) and (35)
as the most surprising of his surprising theorems. But Mally&rsquo;s
reasons for calling these theorems surprising are puzzling if not
confused.</p>

<p>
Consider, for example, theorem (1). Mally interpreted this theorem as
follows: &ldquo;if A requires B, then A requires everything that is
the case&rdquo; (Mally 1926, p. 20). He regarded this as a surprising
claim, and we agree. However, Mally&rsquo;s interpretation of (1) is
not warranted. (1) only says that if A requires B, then A requires the
<em>Verum</em>. The expression &ldquo;if A requires B, then A requires
everything that is the case&rdquo; is to be formalized as</p>

<table class="cellpadd-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>(1&prime;)</td>
  <td>(A f B) &rarr; (C &rarr; (A f C))</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
This formula is an immediate consequence of (1) in virtue of Axiom I.
In other words, Mally should have reasoned as follows: (1&prime;) is
surprising; but (1&prime;) is an immediate consequence of (1) in
virtue of Axiom I; Axiom 1 is uncontroversial; so (1) is to be
regarded as surprising.</p>

<p>
A similar pattern is to be seen in many of Mally&rsquo;s other remarks
about theorems which surprised him. He generally read too much into
them and confused them with some of the consequences they had in his
system:</p>

<ul class="jfy">

<li>Mally was surprised by (2) because he thought that it says that if
A requires B and B is not the case, then A requires every state of
affairs whatsoever (Mally 1926, p. 21). But (2) says no such thing.
Mally&rsquo;s paraphrase is a paraphrase of (A f B) &rarr; (&not;B
&rarr; (A f C)) (a consequence of (2) in virtue of Axiom I) rather
than (2).</li>

<li>Mally paraphrased (7) as &ldquo;if anything is required, then
everything that is the case is required&rdquo; (Mally 1926, p. 28),
which is indeed surprising. However, Mally&rsquo;s paraphrase
corresponds with !A &rarr; (B &rarr; !B) (a consequence of (7) in
virtue of Axiom I) rather than (7).</li>

<li>Mally paraphrased (22) as &ldquo;the facts ought to be the
case&rdquo; (Mally 1926, p. 24). We grant that this is a surprising
claim. But the corresponding formula in Mally&rsquo;s language is A
&rarr; !A (a consequence of (22) in virtue of Axiom I), not (22).</li>

<li>Mally read (27) as &ldquo;if something which ought not to be the
case is the case, then anything whatsoever ought to be the case&rdquo;
(Mally 1926, pp. 24, 33), but this is a paraphrase of !&not;A &rarr;
(A &rarr; !B) (a theorem of Mally&rsquo;s system) rather than
(27).</li>

<li>Mally paraphrased (33) as &ldquo;what is not the case is not
obligatory&rdquo; (Mally 1926, p. 25) and as &ldquo;everything that is
obligatory is the case&rdquo; (Mally 1926, p. 34). These assertions
are indeed surprising, but Mally&rsquo;s readings of (33) are not
warranted. They are paraphrases of !A &rarr; A rather than (33).</li>

<li>Mally made the following remark about (34) and (35):

<blockquote>

<p>
The latter sentences, which seem to identify being obligatory with
being the case, are surely the most surprising of our
&ldquo;surprising
 consequences.&rdquo;<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-7" id="ref-7">7</a>]</sup></p>
 </blockquote>

<p>
However, (34) and (35) do not assert that being obligatory is
equivalent with being the case, for the latter statement should be
formalized as A &harr; !A. The latter formula is a theorem of
Mally&rsquo;s system, as will be shown in a moment, but it is not to
be found in Mally&rsquo;s book.</p></li>
</ul>

<p>
Mally regarded theorems (28)&ndash;(32) as surprising because of their
relationships with certain other surprising theorems:</p>

<ul class="jfy">

<li>(28)&ndash;(30) are instantiations of (27). But this is not
sufficient to call these theorems surprising. Mally actually viewed
(28) as less surprising than (27): one might use it to justify
retaliation and revenge (Mally 1926, p. 24).</li>

<li>(31) implies (28)&ndash;(30) and is therefore at least as
surprising as those theorems.</li>

<li>Mally viewed (32) as surprising because the surprising theorem
(33) is an immediate consequence of (32) and the apparently
non-surprising theorem (25).</li>
</ul>

<p>
Mally&rsquo;s list of surprising theorems seems too short: for
example, (24) is equivalent with A &rarr; !A in virtue of Def. f. But
A &rarr; !A may be paraphrased as &ldquo;the facts ought to be the
case,&rdquo; an assertion which Mally regarded as surprising (Mally
1926, p. 24). So then why didn&rsquo;t he call (24) surprising? Did it
not surprise him after (22)?</p>

<p>
Even though Mally regarded many of his theorems as surprising, he
thought that he had discovered an interesting concept of
&ldquo;correct willing&rdquo; (<em>richtiges Wollen</em>) or
&ldquo;willing in accordance with the facts&rdquo; which should not be
confused with the notions of obligation and willing used in ordinary
discourse. Mally&rsquo;s &ldquo;exact system of pure ethics&rdquo; was
mainly concerned with this concept, but as we said in the Introduction
we will not describe this system because it belongs to the field of
ethics rather than deontic logic.</p>

<h2 id="MengCrit">6. Menger&rsquo;s Criticism and the Deontic Collapse</h2>

<p>
Mally&rsquo;s enterprise was received with little enthusiasm. As early
as 1926, it was noted that &ldquo;Mr. Mally&rsquo;s deductions are
frequently so amazingly obtuse and irrelevant that (despite his
elaborate symbolic apparatus) it is only necessary to state one or two
of them to show how far his discussion has strayed from its
self-appointed task&rdquo; (Laird 1926, p. 395).</p>

<p>
In 1939, Karl Menger published a devastating attack on Mally&rsquo;s
system. He was the first to point out that A &harr; !A, the
&ldquo;deontic collapse&rdquo; (henceforth DC), is a theorem of this
system. In other words, if A is the case, then A is obligatory, and if
A ought to be the case then A is indeed the case. As we have already
noted in connection with theorems (34) and (35), Mally made the same
claim in informal terms, but the formula A &harr; !A does not occur in
his book.</p>

<p>
Menger gave the following comment:</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
This result seems to me to be detrimental for Mally&rsquo;s theory,
however. It indicates that the introduction of the sign ! is
superfluous in the sense that it may be cancelled or inserted in any
formula at any place we please. But this result (in spite of
Mally&rsquo;s philosophical justification) clearly contradicts not
only our use of the word &ldquo;ought&rdquo; but also some of
Mally&rsquo;s own correct remarks about this concept, e.g. the one at
the beginning of his development to the effect that p &rarr; (!q or
!r) and p &rarr; !(q or r) are not equivalent. Mally is quite right
that these two propositions are not equivalent according to the
ordinary use of the word &ldquo;ought.&rdquo; But they are equivalent
according to his theory by virtue of the equivalence of p and !p
(Menger 1939, p. 58).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
Almost all deontic logicians have accepted Menger&rsquo;s verdict.
After 1939, Mally&rsquo;s deontic system has seldom been taken
seriously.</p>

<p>
Menger&rsquo;s theorem A &harr; !A may be proven as follows
(Menger&rsquo;s proof was different; <strong>PC</strong> denotes the
classical propositional calculus).</p>

<p>
First, the left-to-right direction A &rarr; !A (DC<sub>lr</sub>) of DC
is a theorem:</p>

