<p>
<strong>Observe that a close inspection of the proof of the DC theorem
</strong>A &harr;!A <strong>given above shows the
following:</strong></p>

<ul>

<li><strong>the DC<sub>lr</sub> implication </strong>A &rarr;! A is
derivable &mdash; indeed, even on the basis of <em>intuitionistic</em>
propositional calculus (<strong>IPC</strong>) &mdash; using only
axioms <strong>I + IV</strong>, or alternatively <strong>I +
III</strong>;</li>

<li><strong>the DC<sub>rl</sub> implication</strong>!A &rarr;, in
turn, is derivable using only axioms <strong>I + V</strong> &mdash;
but <em>not</em> on the basis of <strong>IPC</strong> in this case
(this is proved in Centrone 2013, p. 4111).</li>
</ul>

<p>
<strong>Hence the infamous deontic collapse DC is already derivable in
the two subsystems of Mally&rsquo;s system determined by the three
axioms I, IV, V, and I, III, V, respectively. Since axioms IV and V,
taken in isolation, are (at least formally) sound, this seems to place
the blame, in particular, on axioms I and III.</strong></p>

<p>
Finally, since <strong>axioms I and IV</strong> suffice to derive
<strong>DC<sub>lr</sub></strong>, one might wonder whether they also
suffice to derive the opposite half, <strong>DC<sub>rl</sub></strong>.
And since <strong>axioms I and V</strong> suffice to derive
<strong>DC<sub>rl</sub></strong>, one might wonder whether they also
suffice to derive the remaining half,
<strong>DC<sub>lr</sub></strong>. <strong>The answer is negative in
both cases:</strong> even working with classical logic (see Centrone
2013, pp. 4107&ndash;4109):</p>

<ul>

<li>!A &rarr; A (DC<sub>rl</sub>) is <em>not</em> derivable from the
set {I, II, III, IV} of axioms, and</li>

<li>A &rarr;!A (DC<sub>lr</sub>) is <em>not</em> derivable from the
set {I, II, V} of axioms.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="WherDidMallGoWron">7. Where Did Mally Go Wrong?</h2>

<p>
Where did Mally go wrong? How could one construct a system of deontic
logic which does more justice to the notion of obligation used in
ordinary discourse? Three kinds of answers are possible:</p>

<ol class="jfy">

<li>Mally should not have added his deontic axioms to classical
propositional logic;</li>

<li>Some of his deontic principles should be modified;</li>

<li>Both of the above.</li>
</ol>

<p>
Menger advocated the first view: &ldquo;One of the reasons for the
failure of Mally&rsquo;s interesting attempt is that it was founded on
the 2-valued calculus of propositions&rdquo; (Menger 1939, p. 59).</p>

<p>
The first two suggestions turn out to be sufficient, so the third
proposal is overkill.</p>

<p>
In the following we will point out three facts:</p>

<p>
First, if Mally&rsquo;s deontic principles are added to a system in
which the so-called paradoxes of material and strict implication are
avoided, many of the &ldquo;surprising&rdquo; theorems (such as (34)
and (35)) are no longer derivable and A &harr; !A is no longer
derivable either (section 8).</p>

<p>
Second, if Mally&rsquo;s deontic principles are added to a system in
which the so-called law of the excluded middle is avoided, the
unacceptable consequence A &harr; !A is no longer derivable, but
almost all theorems that Mally derived himself are still derivable
(section 9).</p>

<p>
Third, if Mally&rsquo;s deontic principles, e.g., Def. f , Axiom I,
Axiom III, are slightly modified, the resulting system is almost
identical with the system nowadays known as standard deontic logic
(section 10).</p>

<h2 id="AlteNonDeonBase1ReleLogi">8. Alternative Non-Deontic Bases 1: Relevance Logic</h2>

<p>
Mally&rsquo;s informal postulates (i)&ndash;(iii) and (v) are
conditionals or negations of conditionals, i.e., of the form &ldquo;if
&hellip; then &mdash;&rdquo; or &ldquo;not: if &hellip; then
&mdash;.&rdquo; F&oslash;llesdal and Hilpinen (1981, pp. 5&ndash;6)
have suggested that such conditionals should not be formalized in
terms of material implication and that some sort of strict implication
would be more appropriate. But this suggestion is not altogether
satisfactory, for both A &rarr;<sub>s</sub> !A and !A
&rarr;<sub>s</sub> A are derivable in the very weak system
<strong>S0.9<sup>0</sup></strong> plus I and III, where
&rarr;<sub>s</sub> is the symbol of strict
 implication.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-10" id="ref-10">10</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
In systems of strict implication the so-called paradoxes of material
implication (such as A &rarr; (B &rarr; A)) are avoided, but the
so-called paradoxes of strict implication (such as (A &amp; &not;A)
&rarr;<sub>s</sub> B) remain. What would happen to Mally&rsquo;s
system if <em>both</em> kinds of paradoxes were avoided? This question
can be answered by adding Mally&rsquo;s axioms to a system in which
none of the so-called &ldquo;fallacies of relevance&rdquo; can be
derived (see the entry on
 <a href="../logic-relevance/">relevance logic</a>).</p>
 
<p>
In the following, we will add Mally&rsquo;s axioms to the prominent
relevance logic <strong>R</strong>. The result is better than in the
case of strict implication: most of the theorems which Mally regarded
as surprising are no longer derivable, and Menger&rsquo;s theorem A
&harr; !A is not derivable either. But many &ldquo;plausible&rdquo;
theorems can still be derived.</p>

<p>
Relevant system <strong>R</strong> with the propositional constant t
(&ldquo;the conjunction of all truths&rdquo;) has the following axioms
and rules (Anderson &amp; Belnap 1975, ch. V; &harr; is defined by A
&harr; B = (A &rarr; B) &amp; (B &rarr; A)):</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>Self-implication.</td>
  <td>A &rarr; A</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Prefixing.</td>
  <td>(A &rarr; B) &rarr; ((C &rarr; A) &rarr; (C &rarr; B))</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>Contraction.</td>
  <td>(A &rarr; (A &rarr; B)) &rarr; (A &rarr; B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Permutation.</td>
  <td>(A &rarr; (B &rarr; C)) &rarr; (B &rarr; (A &rarr; C))</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>&amp; Elimination.</td>
  <td>(A &amp; B) &rarr; A, (A &amp; B) &rarr; B</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td class="nw">&amp; Introduction.</td>
  <td class="nw">((A &rarr; B) &amp; (A &rarr; C)) &rarr; (A &rarr; (B
&amp; C))</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>&or; Introduction.</td>
  <td>A &rarr; (A &or; B), B &rarr; (A &or; B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>&or; Elimination.</td>
  <td>((A &rarr; C) &amp; (B &rarr; C)) &rarr; ((A &or; B) &rarr;
C)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Distribution.</td>
  <td>(A &amp; (B &or; C)) &rarr; ((A &amp; B) &or; C)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Double Negation.</td>
  <td>&not;&not;A &rarr; A</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Contraposition.</td>
  <td>(A &rarr; &not;B) &rarr; (B &rarr; &not;A)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Ax. t.</td>
  <td>A &harr; (t &rarr; A)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Modus Ponens.</td>
  <td>A, A &rarr; B / B</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Adjunction.</td>
  <td>A, B / A &amp; B</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
A relevant version <strong>RD</strong> of Mally&rsquo;s deontic system
may be defined as follows:</p>

<ul class="jfy">

<li>The language is the same as the language of <strong>R</strong>,
except that we write V instead of t, add the propositional constant U
and the unary connective !, and define &Lambda;, &cap;, f and &infin;
as in Mally&rsquo;s system.</li>

<li>Axiomatization: add Mally&rsquo;s Axioms I-V to the axioms and
rules of <strong>R</strong>.</li>
</ul>

<p>
<strong>RD</strong> has the following properties.</p>

<ul>

<li>Axioms I, II and III may be replaced by the following three
simpler
 axioms:<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-11" id="ref-11">11</a>]</sup>
 
<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>I*.</td>
  <td>(A &rarr; B) &rarr; (!A &rarr; !B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>II*.</td>
  <td>(!A &amp; !B) &rarr; !(A &amp; B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>III*.</td>
  <td>!(!A &rarr; A)</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table></li>

<li>Formulas I&ndash;V, (3), (4), (6), (8)&ndash;(11), (14),
(16)&ndash;(18), (23&prime;) and (30) are theorems of
 <strong>RD</strong>.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-12" id="ref-12">12</a>]</sup></li>
 
<li>Formulas (1), (2), (5), (7), (12), (13), (15), (19)&ndash;(23),
(24)&ndash;(29), (31)&ndash;(35), A &rarr; !A and !A &rarr; A are not
 derivable.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-13" id="ref-13">13</a>]</sup></li>
 
<li>There are 12 mismatches between <strong>RD</strong> and
Mally&rsquo;s expectations: (5), (12)&ndash;(13), (15),
(19)&ndash;(21), (23) and (24)&ndash;(26) are not derivable even
though Mally did not regard these formulas as surprising, and (30) is
a theorem even though Mally viewed it as surprising.</li>

<li>Formulas (34) and (35) (the formulas which Mally viewed as the
most surprising theorems of his system) are in a sense stranger than
Menger&rsquo;s theorem A &harr; !A because the latter theorem is
derivable in <strong>RD</strong> supplemented with (34) or (35) while
neither (34) nor (35) is derivable in <strong>RD</strong> supplemented
with A &harr;
 !A.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-14" id="ref-14">14</a>]</sup></li>
 </ul>

<p>
Although most of Mally&rsquo;s surprising theorems are not derivable
in <strong>RD</strong>, this has nothing to do with Mally&rsquo;s own
reasons for regarding these theorems as surprising. They are not
derivable in <strong>RD</strong> because they depend on fallacies of
relevance. Mally never referred to such fallacies to explain his
surprise. His considerations were quite different, as we have already
described.</p>

<p>
<strong>RD</strong> is closely related to Anderson&rsquo;s relevant
deontic logic <strong>ARD</strong>, which is defined as
<strong>R</strong> supplemented with the following two axioms
(Anderson 1967, 1968, McArthur 1981; Anderson used the unary
connective O instead of !):</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>ARD1.</td>
  <td>!A &harr; (&not;A &rarr; &cap;)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>ARD2.</td>
  <td>!A &rarr; &not;!&not;A</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<ul class="jfy">

<li>All theorems of <strong>RD</strong> are theorems of
 <strong>ARD</strong>.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-15" id="ref-15">15</a>]</sup></li>
 
<li>ARD1( &rarr; ) is not a theorem of
 <strong>RD</strong>+ARD2.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-16" id="ref-16">16</a>]</sup>
 This formula does not occur in Mally&rsquo;s book. According to
Anderson, Bohnert (1945) was the first one to propose
 it.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-17" id="ref-17">17</a>]</sup></li>
 
<li>ARD2 is not a theorem of
 <strong>RD</strong>+ARD1.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-18" id="ref-18">18</a>]</sup>
 This formula does not occur in Mally&rsquo;s book, but Mally endorsed
the corresponding informal principle: &ldquo;a person who wills
correctly does not will (not even implicitly) the negation of what he
wills; correct willing is free of
 contradictions.&rdquo;<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-19" id="ref-19">19</a>]</sup></li>
 
<li><strong>RD</strong> supplemented with ARD1( &rarr; ) and ARD2 has
the same theorems as
 <strong>ARD</strong>.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-20" id="ref-20">20</a>]</sup></li>
 </ul>

<p>
Anderson&rsquo;s system has several problematical features (McArthur
1981, Goble 1999, 2001) and <strong>RD</strong> shares most of these
features. But we will not go into this issue here. It is at any rate
clear that <strong>RD</strong> is better than Mally&rsquo;s original
system.</p>

<h2 id="AlteNonDeonBase2IntuLogi">9. Alternative Non-Deontic Bases 2: Intuitionistic Logic</h2>

<p>
It was recently pointed out that it is also possible to base
Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic on intuitionistic propositional logic
<strong>IPC</strong> rather than classical propositional logic
(Lokhorst 2013 &amp; 2015; see also Centrone 2013).</p>

<p>
Heyting&rsquo;s intuitionistic propositional calculus
<strong>IPC</strong> has the following axioms and rules (see Van Dalen
2002 and the entry on
 <a href="../logic-intuitionistic/">intuitionistic logic</a>):</p>
 
<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>A &rarr; (B &rarr; A)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>(A &rarr; (B &rarr; C)) &rarr; ((A &rarr; B) &rarr; (A &rarr;
C))</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>(A &amp; B) &rarr; A</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>(A &amp; B) &rarr; B</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>A &rarr; (B &rarr; (A &amp; B))</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>A &rarr; (A &or; B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>B &rarr; (A &or; B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>(A &rarr; C) &rarr; ((B &rarr; C) &rarr; ((A &or; B) &rarr;
C))</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>&perp; &rarr; A</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td><em>modus ponens</em></td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td><em>substitution</em></td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>&nbsp;</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
If we add to these axioms and rules the following:</p>

<p>
Abbreviations: &not; A = A &rarr; &perp;, A &harr; B = (A &rarr; B)
&amp; (B &rarr; A), T = A &rarr; A,</p>

<p>
then we can formulate <strong>ID</strong> (an intuitionistic
reformulation of Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic) as <strong>IPC</strong>
plus Mally&rsquo;s axioms I &ndash; V and</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>(34)</td>
  <td>U &harr; T</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>VI</td>
  <td>!(A &or; &not; A)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>&nbsp;</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
Axiom VI follows from Mally&rsquo;s theorem (12d) (see Mally 1926, ch.
2, sec. 5, p. 29 and Morscher 1998, p.
 122).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-21" id="ref-21">21</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
FACT 1. <strong>ID</strong> can alternatively be axiomatized as
<strong>IPC</strong> plus axioms !A &harr; &not; &not; A and
 (34).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-22" id="ref-22">22</a>]</sup></p>
 Classical propositional logic, <strong>CPC</strong>, is
<strong>IPC</strong> plus A &or; &not; A. <strong>MD</strong>
(&ldquo;Mally&rsquo;s <em>Deontik</em>&rdquo;) is <strong>ID</strong>
plus <strong>CPC</strong>.

<p>
FACT 2. A &harr; !A is a theorem of
 <strong>MD</strong>.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-23" id="ref-23">23</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
In modern deontic logic, P A (&ldquo;it is permitted that A&rdquo;) is
defined as P A = &not; !&not; A. If we adopt this definition,
<strong>ID</strong> provides !A &harr; P A (because
<strong>IPC</strong> provides &not; &not; A &harr; &not; &not; &not;
&not; A). Mally did not discuss permission. His approval of !A &rarr;
&not; !&not; A (which is usually regarded as characteristic for
deontic logic) is clear from Mally 1926, ch. 4, sec. 10, p. 49,
<em>ad</em> (V).</p>

<p>
Mally objected to !(A &or; B) &rarr; (!A &or; !B) and Menger objected
to A &harr; !A (see Mally 1926, ch. 2, sec. 4, p. 27, <em>ad</em> (II)
and the quote in Section 6 above). <strong>ID</strong> avoids these
objections:</p>

<p>
FACT 3. Neither !(A &or; B) &rarr; (!A &or; !B) nor !A &rarr; A is a
theorem of
 <strong>ID</strong>.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-24" id="ref-24">24</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
Only one of the theorems presented by Mally is <em>not</em> derivable
in <strong>ID</strong>, namely (13b): &not; (A &amp; &not; !B) &harr;
(&not; A &or;
 !B).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-25" id="ref-25">25</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
FACT 4. For any extension X of <strong>ID</strong> (in the language of
<strong>ID</strong>): X provides (13b) if and only if X provides !(A
&or; B) &rarr; (!A &or;
 !B).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-26" id="ref-26">26</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
<strong>ID</strong> plus (13b) does not provide !A &rarr;
 A.<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-27" id="ref-27">27</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
The intuitionistic reformulation of Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic that
we have proposed is successful in so far as it avoids both
Menger&rsquo;s and Mally&rsquo;s own objections while preserving
almost all the theorems that Mally noticed himself. However, it is
unacceptable as a system of deontic logic in its own right. We mention
only two reasons:</p>

<p>
1. Theorem A &rarr; !A is intuitively invalid. No deontic system,
except Mally&rsquo;s, has this theorem.</p>

<p>
2. It is unclear how permission is to be represented. If we use the
standard definition (P A = &not; !&not; A), then P A &harr; !A is a
theorem, but P A and !A are not equivalent according to the ordinary
use of the words &ldquo;permitted&rdquo; and
&ldquo;obligatory.&rdquo;</p>

<p>
The relevantist reformulation of Mally&rsquo;s system that was
discussed above does not have these defects.</p>

<p>
Although <strong>ID</strong> is unacceptable as a system of deontic
logic, it does make sense as a system of <em>lax logic</em>, as we
will now show. Lax logic is used in the areas of hardware verification
in digital circuits and access control in secure systems, where !
expresses a notion of correctness up to constraints. The term
&ldquo;lax&rdquo; was chosen &ldquo;to indicate the looseness
associated with the notion of correctness up to constraints&rdquo;
(Fairtlough and Mendler 1997, p. 3). There is a considerable
literature on lax logic (see a.o. Goldblatt 2011, Iemhoff 2024).</p>

<p>
Propositional lax logic <strong>PLL</strong> is defined as
<strong>IPC</strong> plus (A &rarr; !B) &harr; (!A &rarr; !B)
(Fairtlough and Mendler 1997, p. 4, Lemma 2.1). Lax logic
<strong>PLL*</strong> is <strong>PLL</strong> plus !A &harr; &not;
&not; A (Fairtlough and Mendler 1997, p. 23).</p>

<p>
FACT 5. <strong>ID</strong> is an alternative axiomatization of lax
logic <strong>PLL*</strong> plus
 (34).<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-28" id="ref-28">28</a>]</sup></p>
 
<p>
Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic and lax logic arose from quite different
considerations. It is therefore remarkable that the intuitionistic
reformulation of Mally&rsquo;s logic that we have discussed is
identical with lax logic <strong>PLL*</strong> plus (34).</p>

<h2 id="AlteDeonPrin">10. Alternative Deontic Principles</h2>

<p>
Instead of changing the non-deontic propositional basis of
Mally&rsquo;s system, one might instead modify the specifically
deontic axioms. This might of course be done in various ways; here we
consider two approaches that work well without straying too far from
Mally&rsquo;s original assumptions.</p>

<p>
Preliminarily, we recall that the so-called standard system of deontic
logic <strong>KD</strong> &ndash; where !, V and &Lambda; are usually
written as O, &#8868; and &perp; (see the entry on
 <a href="../logic-deontic/">deontic logic</a>),
 but we keep Mally&rsquo;s symbols for ease of comparison &ndash; is
the normal modal system that can be defined as <strong>PC</strong>
supplemented in one of the two following ways:</p>

<table class="all-rules cellpad-med centered" style="width:500px">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td><strong>KD &ndash; version 1</strong></td>
  <td><strong>KD &ndash; version 2</strong></td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td><em>Inference rule:</em></td>
  <td><em>Inference rule:</em></td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>Rd: B &rarr; C / !B &rarr; !C</td>
  <td>RN: A / !A</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td><em>Axioms:</em></td>
  <td><em>Axioms:</em></td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>i: (!A &amp; !B) &rarr; !(A &amp; B)</td>
  <td>K: !(A &rarr; B) &rarr; (!A &rarr; !B)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>ii: !V</td>
  <td>D &not;!&Lambda; (or: !A &rarr; &not;!&not;A)</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>iii: &not;!&Lambda;</td>
  <td>&nbsp;</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
The standard system of deontic logic has several problematical
features. The fact that each provable statement is obligatory is often
regarded as counterintuitive, and there are many other well-known
&ldquo;paradoxes.&rdquo; The revised versions of Mally&rsquo;s system
we are going to consider share these problematical features. But we
will not discuss these issues here. The standard system is at any rate
better than Mally&rsquo;s original proposal.</p>

<p>
<strong>10.1. </strong> In the first
 approach<sup>[<a href="notes.html#note-29" id="ref-29">29</a>]</sup>,
 to begin with, the operator f is regarded as primitive and
Mally&rsquo;s definition of f in terms of &rarr; and ! (Def. f, the
very first specifically deontic postulate in Mally&rsquo;s book) is
replaced by the following definition of ! in terms of V and f :</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>Def. !.</td>
  <td>!A = V f A</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
Second, Axiom I, which may also be written as (B &rarr; C) &rarr; ((A
f B) &rarr; (A f C)), is replaced with the following <em>rule of
inference</em>:</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>Rule f.</td>
  <td>B &rarr; C / (A f B) &rarr; (A f C)</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
All the remaining axioms are stated in their original form.</p>

<p>
In the resulting system <strong>MD</strong> one may then derive:</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>1.</td>
  <td>B &rarr; C / !B &rarr; !C</td>
  <td>[ Def. !, Rule f ]</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>2.</td>
  <td>(!A &amp; !B) &rarr; !(A &amp; B)</td>
  <td>[ Def. !, Ax. II ]</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>3.</td>
  <td>!V</td>
  <td>[ 1, Ax. IV, <strong>PC</strong> ]</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>4.</td>
  <td>&not;!&Lambda;</td>
  <td>[ 1, Ax. III(&larr;), Ax. V, <strong>PC</strong> (ex falso)
]</td> </tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
So the new system <strong>MD</strong> is at least as strong as
<strong>KD (</strong>see the above table, version 1<strong>).</strong>
It is not difficult to see that it is in fact identical with
<strong>KD</strong> supplemented with OU (Mally&rsquo;s Axiom IV) and
the following definition of f :</p>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>(Transl<sub>f</sub>)</td>
  <td>A f B = O(A &rarr; B) (in modern deontic logic, the notion of
<em>commitment</em> is sometimes defined in this way)</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>
In this new system, Mally&rsquo;s theorems have the following status
(caution: here I&prime;, II&prime;, III&prime;, IV&prime;, and
V&prime; are Mally&rsquo;s axioms written in terms of the primitive
operators; see the right column of the table in section 3):</p>

<ul class="jfy">

<li>II&prime;, IV&prime;, (1)&ndash;(5), (7)&ndash;(11),
(13)&ndash;(15), (17), (20)&ndash;(24) and (27)&ndash;(32) are
derivable.</li>

<li>I&prime;, III&prime;, V&prime;, (6), (12), (16), (18)&ndash;(19),
(25)&ndash;(26), (33)&ndash;(35), A &rarr; !A and !A &rarr; A are not
derivable.</li>

<li>There are 20 mismatches with Mally&rsquo;s deontic expectations:
10 &ldquo;plausible&rdquo; formulas are no longer derivable, namely
I&prime;, III&prime;, V&prime;, (6), (12), (16), (18)&ndash;(19) and
(25)&ndash;(26), and 10 &ldquo;surprising&rdquo; theorems are still
derivable, namely (1), (2), (7), (22) and (27)&ndash;(32).</li>

<li>Although (34) and (35) are not derivable, adding them would by no
means lead to the theoremhood of A &harr; !A.</li>
</ul>

<p>
There were only 12 mismatches in the case of <strong>RD</strong>, so
<strong>MD</strong> does less justice to Mally&rsquo;s deontic
expectations than <strong>RD</strong> did. But it agrees better with
his general outlook because it is still based on classical
propositional logic, a system to which Mally did not object (not that
he had much choice in the 1920s).</p>

<p>
Many of Mally&rsquo;s surprising theorems are derivable in
<strong>KD</strong>, but they have, as it were, lost their sting:
those theorems lead to surprising consequences when combined with
Mally&rsquo;s Axiom I and his definition of f , but they are
completely harmless without these postulates.</p>

<p>
<strong>10.2.</strong> A different way of amending Mally&rsquo;s
system by modifying the axioms is introduced and examined in Centrone
2013, pp. 4110 ff. The proposed amended system, called
<strong>Mm</strong>, has the same language as Mally&rsquo;s original
system <strong>M</strong> and is obtained from the latter as follows,
<em>without changing Mally&rsquo;s definition of</em> f:</p>

<ul>

<li>Axiom I is replaced with one (at choice) of its associated
inference rules:</li>
</ul>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>Rule RI</td>
  <td>A &rarr; !B / (B &rarr; C) &rarr; (A &rarr; !C)</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<table class="cellpad-med-dense indent vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>Rule RI&acute;</td>
  <td>(B &rarr; C) / (A &rarr; !B) &rarr; (A &rarr; !C)</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<ul>

<li>Axiom III is dropped.</li>
</ul>

<p>
The language of <strong>Mm</strong> is properly included in that of
<strong>KD</strong> (which does not have the sentential constant U)
&ndash; therefore every <strong>Mm</strong>-formula is a
<strong>KD</strong>-formula, but not vice versa. To make the two
systems comparable, each <strong>Mm</strong>-formula A is associated
with the <strong>KD</strong>-formula A* obtained from A by replacing U
everywhere with &#8868;. It can then be proved that
<strong>Mm</strong> and <strong>KD</strong> are equivalent modulo the
translation *. More precisely, the following holds:</p>

<p>
&bull; For every <strong>KD</strong>-formula A, if A is a theorem of
<strong>KD</strong>, then A is a theorem of <strong>Mm</strong>;
<br />
&bull; for every <strong>Mm</strong>-formula A, if A is a theorem of
<strong>Mm</strong>, then A* is a theorem of <strong>KD</strong>;
<br />
&bull; moreover, for every <strong>Mm</strong>-formula A, A &harr; A*
is a theorem of <strong>Mm</strong>.</p>

<p>
The system <strong>MD</strong> considered in 10.1 seems, at least
<em>prima facie</em>, closer to Mally&rsquo;s original system than the
system <strong>Mm</strong>, insofar as it retains all of Mally&rsquo;s
axioms except Axiom I, which, as in <strong>Mm</strong>, is turned
into an inference rule (but in <strong>MD</strong> the rule is
formulated using the operator f, which is taken as primitive).</p>

<p>
In particular, <strong>MD</strong> includes Mally&rsquo;s
controversial Axiom III, (A f B) &harr; !(A &rarr; B), which is
instead dropped in <strong>Mm</strong>. This, however, is possible
only at the cost of rejecting another of Mally&rsquo;s commitments,
namely his definition of A f B (in terms of !) as A &rarr; !B. Indeed,
once translated into <strong>KD</strong> + OU according to the
definition (Transl<sub>f</sub>), Axiom III loses its problematic
character and becomes the harmless (A &rarr; B) &harr; !(&#8868;
&rarr; (A &rarr; B)).</p>

<h2 id="Conc">11. Conclusion</h2>

<p>
Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic is unacceptable for the reasons stated by
Menger (1939). But it is not as bad as it may seem at first sight.
Only relatively minor modifications are needed to turn it into a more
acceptable system. One may either change the non-deontic basis to get
either a system that is similar to Anderson&rsquo;s system or a system
that is identical with intuitionistic or constructive propositional
logic with double negation as an obligation-like operator, or apply
two patches to the deontic postulates to obtain a system similar to
standard deontic logic.</p>

<p>
Some authors have refused to view Mally&rsquo;s deontic logic as a
&ldquo;real&rdquo; deontic system and say that they &ldquo;mention it
only by way of curiosity&rdquo; (Meyer and Wieringa 1993, p. 4). The
above shows that this judgment is too harsh. It is only a small step,
not a giant leap, from Mally&rsquo;s system to modern systems of
deontic logic, so Mally&rsquo;s pioneering effort deserves
rehabilitation rather than contempt.</p>
</div>

